---
source: crates/normalize/tests/cli_snapshots.rs
expression: "snapshot_help(&[])"
---
Structural code intelligence: index symbols and calls, enforce rules, track complexity.

Usage: normalize [OPTIONS] [COMMAND]

Commands:
  grep       Search for text patterns across the codebase using ripgrep regex syntax.
  aliases    List filter aliases (used by --exclude/--only)
  context    Show directory context (hierarchical .context.md files)
  init       Initialize normalize in current directory
  update     Check for and install updates
  translate  Translate code between programming languages
  ci         Run all configured quality checks and exit non-zero if any errors are found.
  view       View a node in the codebase tree, or navigate symbol relationships
  daemon     Manage the global normalize daemon
  grammars   Manage tree-sitter grammars for parsing
  guide      Workflow guides with examples
  generate   Generate code from API spec
  structure  Manage the structural index (symbols, imports, calls)
  syntax     AST inspection and syntax rules
  package    Package management: info, list, tree, outdated
  sessions   Analyze agent session logs (Claude Code, Codex, Gemini)
  tools      External ecosystem tools (linters, formatters, test runners)
  edit       Structural editing of code symbols
  analyze    Analyze codebase (health, complexity, security, duplicates, docs)
  rank       Rank code by metrics (complexity, size, coupling, duplicates, and more)
  budget     Track diff-based budgets (limits on how much things can change)
  ratchet    Track metric regressions with a ratchet baseline
  rules      Manage and run syntax/fact rules
  config     Inspect and validate config files using JSON Schema
  serve      Start a normalize server (MCP, HTTP, LSP)
  help       Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)

Options:
      --pretty                     Human-friendly output with colors and formatting
      --compact                    Compact output without colors (overrides TTY detection)
      --jsonl                      Output one JSON object per line (for arrays)
      --json                       Output machine-readable JSON
      --jq <jq>                    Filter output through jq expression
      --input-schema               Print JSON Schema of the subcommand's input parameters and exit
      --output-schema              Print JSON Schema of the subcommand's return type and exit
      --params-json <params-json>  Provide all parameters as a JSON object instead of individual flags
  -h, --help                       Print help
  -V, --version                    Print version
